"Julliard R., Jiguet F., Couvet D.","Evidence for the impact of global warming on the long-term population dynamics of common birds",2004,"Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","271","SUPPL. 6",,"S490","S492",,,10.1098/rsbl.2004.0229,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-17044364010&partnerID=40&md5=27e8b1fbc87642e454c9fa6cfc8cb6d2","Ctr. Rech. Biol. des Pop. d'Oiseaux, Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 55, Rue Buffon, F-75005 Paris, France","Julliard, R., Ctr. Rech. Biol. des Pop. d'Oiseaux, Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 55, Rue Buffon, F-75005 Paris, France; Jiguet, F., Ctr. Rech. Biol. des Pop. d'Oiseaux, Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 55, Rue Buffon, F-75005 Paris, France; Couvet, D., Ctr. Rech. Biol. des Pop. d'Oiseaux, Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 55, Rue Buffon, F-75005 Paris, France","Taking the opportunity in 2003 of the exceptionally warm spring in France as a natural simulation of possible future climate, we analysed common bird productivity using the French long-term capture-recapture national monitoring scheme. Two-thirds of the 32 species studied had an above-average productivity in 2003. However, this gain in productivity was not consistent among species, with a relatively low productivity for species exhibiting a long-term decline and relatively high productivity for stable or increasing species. Such links between long-term and short-term dynamics suggest that the impact of increasingly warm springs on productivity is a major component of the recent population dynamics of a variety of common bird species. ©2004 The Royal Society.","Capture-recapture; Country-wide long-term monitoring; Europe; France; Productivity","avifauna; biological production; climate change; global warming; population dynamics; article; bird; environmental monitoring; Europe; France; greenhouse effect; nonhuman; population dynamics; priority journal; reproduction; temperature; Animals; Birds; France; Greenhouse Effect; Logistic Models; Models, Biological; Population Dynamics; Reproduction; Species Specificity; Temperature; Time Factors; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Europe; France; Western Europe; World",,,,,,"DeSante, D.F., O'Grady, D.R., Pyle, P., Measures of productivity and survival derived from standardized mist-netting are consistent with observed population changes (1999) Bird Study, 46 (SUPPL. 1), pp. S178-S188; Dunn, P.O., Winkler, D.W., Climate change has affected the breeding date of tree swallows throughout North America (1999) Proc. R. Soc. Lond. B, 266, pp. 2487-2490. , DOI 10.1098/rspb.1999.0950; Gregory, R.D., Wilkinson, N.I., Noble, D.G., Robinson, J.A., Brown, A.F., Hughes, J., Procter, D., Galbraith, C.A., The population status of birds in the United Kingdom, Channel Islands and Isle of Man: An analysis of conservation concern 2002-2007 (2002) British Birds, 95, pp. 410-448; Julliard, R., Jiguet, J., Un suivis intégré des populations d'oiseaux communs en France (2002) Alauda, 70, pp. 137-147; Julliard, R., Jiguet, J., Couvet, D., Common birds facing global changes: What makes a species at risk? (2003) Global Change Biol., 10, pp. 148-154; (2004) Le Climat pour la France en 2003, , www.meteo.fr/meteonet/actu/archives/dossiers/bilan2003; Moisselin, J.M., Schneider, M., Canellas, C., Mestre, O., Climate change over France during the 20th century: A study of long-term homogenized data of temperature and rainfall (2002) La Météorologie, 38, pp. 45-56. , In French with English summary; Parmesan, C., Yohe, G.A., A globally coherent fingerprint of climate change impacts across natural systems (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 37-42; Peach, W.J., Buckland, S.T., Baillie, S.R., The use of constant effort mist-netting to measure between-year changes in the abundance and productivity of common passerines (1996) Bird Study, 43, pp. 142-156; Raven, M.J., Noble, D.G., Baillie, S.R., (2003) The Breeding Bird Survey 2002. BTO Research Report 364, , Thetford, UK: British Trust for Ornitho